# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1975-world-series
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1975-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1882 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1975-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] It was the first season for the team as a member of the American Association.
[src:1975-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] This team took the nickname from the previous National League team that played during 1876–1879, but was otherwise unrelated.
[src:1975-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings (sometimes called the "Reds") won the first American Association championship this season.
[src:1975-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Before the season began, the Red Stockings named catcher Pop Snyder as the player-manager.
[src:1975-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Snyder spent the 1881 season with the Boston Red Caps of the National League, hitting .228 with 16 RBI.
[src:1975-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati also signed some familiar players, as Will White and Hick Carpenter spent time with the Cincinnati Reds of the National League.
[src:1975-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] White saw limited action with the Detroit Wolverines, while Carpenter hit .216 with two home runs and 31 RBI with the Worcester Worcesters during the 1881 season.
[src:1975-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Carpenter had a breakout season, as he led the AA with 67 RBI and 120 hits, and led the Red Stockings with a .342 batting average.
[src:1975-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Snyder hit .291 with a homer and 50 RBI, while Joe Sommer hit .288 with a homer, 29 RBI and a team high 82 runs, while leading the league with 354 at-bats.
[src:1975-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, White returned to his 1879 form, as he led the AA with 40 wins, while posting a 1.54 ERA in 480 innings pitched.
[src:1975-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings lost their first ever game, as the Pittsburgh Alleghenys defeated Cincinnati 10–9 at Bank Street Grounds.
[src:1975-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team hovered around the .500 level, as they had a record of 8–9 record in their first 17 games, sitting in fourth place.
[src:1975-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings then went on a 10-game winning streak and rose to first place in the American Association.
[src:1975-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati stayed hot for the rest of the season, finishing with a 55–25 record and winning the American Association pennant, 11.5 games ahead of the second place Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1975-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The **1882 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through October 2, 1882.
[src:1975-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] It was the inaugural season for the American Association (AA) and seventh season for the National League (NL).
[src:1975-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Red Stockings won the AA pennant, while the Chicago White Stockings won the NL pennant.
[src:1975-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association was established as a six-team league in cities not represented by the National League.
[src:1975-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The AA was established with the expectation that it would have more of a "liberal policy" and better labor relations, threatening the puritanical NL, which itself had formal behavior codes with associated policies and procedures and a blacklist for players who did not comply to said rules.
[src:1975-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The AA also refused to recognize the NL's reserve lists.
[src:1975-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Three of the six teams of the American Association survive to this day as National League teams; the Cincinnati Red Stockings, Pittsburgh Alleghenys, and St.
[src:1975-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings are today's Cincinnati Reds, Pittsburgh Pirates, and St.
[src:1975-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 season was the last for the Troy Trojans and Worcester Worcesters.
[src:1975-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 schedule consisted of 80 games for all teams in the six-team American Association, and 84 games for all teams in the eight-team National League.
[src:1975-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Each American Association team was scheduled to play 16 games against the other five teams, while each National League was scheduled to play 12 games against the other seven teams.
[src:1975-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 80-game format was unique to the American Association's 1882 season.
[src:1975-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Meanwhile, the National League had been playing their 84-game schedule, since 1879, though 1882 would be their last.
[src:1975-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see both leagues take on a 98-game format, playing 14 games each against their seven opponents.
[src:1975-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all eight teams, while American Association Opening Day took place on May 2, featuring all six teams.
[src:1975-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The National League would see its final day of the regular season on October 2 featuring a game between the Boston Red Caps and Providence Grays, while the American Association would see its final day of the regular season on October 1, featuring a game between the Louisville Eclipse and St.
[src:1975-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] 5 tie games (1 in AA, 4 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season (though in the National League, standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:1975-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles and Pittsburgh Alleghenys had one tie game each.
[src:1975-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Detroit Wolverines had three tie games.
[src:1975-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues and Troy Trojans had two tie games each.
[src:1975-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:1975-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans leave Haymakers' Grounds (where they played for two seasons) and move to the Troy Ball Clubs Grounds, where they would play until they folded at the end of the season.
[src:1975-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans continue to host a few games at Riverside Park in nearby Greenbush, New York, playing their first three home games of the season, May 16–18, as well as a fourth game on game 1 of a doubleheader May 30 at the park.
[src:1975-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 season saw three teams play their final games at respective ballparks, before moving to new ballparks for the 1883 season.
[src:1975-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1883 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1975-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team finished third in the American Association with a record of 61–37, 5 games behind the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1975-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings came into the 1883 season looking to repeat as American Association Champions, as they had a league best record of 55–25 in 1882.
[src:1975-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] During the off-season, the team announced that catcher Pop Snyder would return as player-manager.
[src:1975-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati also made a big signing, as they signed Charley Jones, who played with the Cincinnati Reds of the National League from 1876–1878.
[src:1975-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Jones had not played professional baseball since 1880, when he played for the Boston Red Caps of the NL, after which he was black-balled from professional baseball.
[src:1975-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings also signed another former Reds player, John Reilly, who had also last played major league baseball for the Reds in the 1880 season.
[src:1975-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the diamond, the Red Stockings were led by Jones, who hit .294 with a team leading ten home runs, as well as a league leading 80 RBI.
[src:1975-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Reilly hit a team high .311 with nine homers and 79 RBI.
[src:1975-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, Will White continued to be the ace of the pitching staff, posting a 43–22 record with 64 complete games and a 2.09 ERA in 577 innings pitched.
[src:1975-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati started off the season on the right foot, winning their first four games, and had an impressive 11–5 record in their first sixteen ballgames.
[src:1975-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] However, they were 3.5 games behind the Athletics.
[src:1975-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings would continue to play good baseball, and had a 31–23 record.
[src:1975-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati would then go on to win twelve of their next thirteen games to improve to 43–24.
[src:1975-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] However, they only moved up to third place.
[src:1975-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings would remain in third place for the rest of the season, finishing the year at 61–37, five games behind the Athletics.
[src:1975-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1884 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1975-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team finished fifth in the American Association with a record of 68–41, 8 games behind the New York Metropolitans.
[src:1975-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings were looking to return to their 1882 form, when they won the American Association pennant before falling to third place in 1883.
[src:1975-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The club named pitcher Will White the player-manager for the 1884 season, taking over for catcher Pop Snyder.
[src:1975-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati was relatively quiet during the off-season, although they did sign Tom Mansell, who had split the previous season between the Detroit Wolverines of the National League, and the St.
[src:1975-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Louis Browns of the AA, hitting .305 with 34 RBI and 45 runs between those two teams.
[src:1975-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The club also moved into American Park for the 1884 season.
[src:1975-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] John Reilly was the offensive force on the team, hitting .339 with eleven home runs and 91 RBI, all club highs.
[src:1975-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Charley Jones hit .314 with seven home runs and 71 RBI, along with a team high 117 runs.
[src:1975-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, White led the way with a 34–18 record and a 3.32 ERA in 52 starts.
[src:1975-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati got off to a slow start, as they lost their first game in their new ballpark, 10–9 to the Columbus Buckeyes, and they had a record of 4–5 in their first nine games, before reeling off four wins in a row to stay above the .500 level for the rest of the season.
[src:1975-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings got red hot, as they eventually had a 28–14 record, only one game out of first place.
[src:1975-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] In a three-game series against the Washington Nationals, the Red Stockings outscored their opposition 48–6.
[src:1975-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati started to fade as the season continued on, and with their record at 44–27 changed managers, bringing Pop Snyder back as player-manager.
[src:1975-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati continued to slump, falling to 10½ games out of first place with a 52–35 record, but then won ten games in a row to climb back to within 4½ games.
[src:1975-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] It was too little too late though, as Cincinnati finished the season with a 68–41 record, good enough for fifth place, eight games behind the Metropolitans.
[src:1975-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1885 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1975-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team finished second in the American Association, 16 games behind the St.
[src:1975-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] During the off-season, the Red Stockings hired O.
[src:1975-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Caylor to become the manager of the team, the first time in club history that the club did not have a player-manager.
[src:1975-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati also signed Tony Mullane to a contract.
[src:1975-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Mullane, who spent the 1884 season with the Toledo Blue Stockings, had a 36–26 record with a 2.52 ERA in 67 starts, striking out 325 batters.
[src:1975-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Mullane was suspended for the 1885 season for defying his contract, as the Blue Stockings and the St.
[src:1975-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Louis Maroons, another team he tried to sign with, folded after the 1884 season, and the St.
[src:1975-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Louis Browns attempted to reclaim Mullane, as he pitched there in 1883.
[src:1975-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Before the Browns could reclaim him, he signed with the Red Stockings.
[src:1975-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Frank Fennelly, who the Red Stockings acquired late in the 1884 season from the Washington Nationals, had a breakout season, hitting .273 with ten home runs and a league high 89 RBI.
[src:1975-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Charley Jones led the team with a .322 average, and had five home runs and 35 RBI to go along with it, while John Reilly hit .297 with five homers and 60 RBI.
[src:1975-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, nineteen-year-old Larry McKeon led the Red Stockings with 20 wins and a 2.86 ERA in 33 starts, while Will White had eighteen wins and a 3.53 ERA in 34 starts.
[src:1975-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati began the season very well, putting up an impressive 16–8 record in their first 24 games to sit in second place in the league, two games behind the St.
[src:1975-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings then began to slump, as they would win only six of their next sixteen games to slip into third place, seven games behind the Browns.
[src:1975-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On July 1, the Red Stockings acquired Jim Keenan and Larry McKeon, who both jumped from the Detroit Wolverines to join Cincinnati.
[src:1975-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings improved with their new acquisitions in the lineup, as the team eventually moved back into second place, however, they were too far behind the Browns, and Cincinnati finished the season with a 63–49 record, good for second place, however, they were sixteen games out of first.
[src:1975-world-series/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1886 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1975-world-series/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings finished in fifth place in the American Association, 27.5 games behind the St.
[src:1975-world-series/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Pop Corkhill had a breakout season, hitting .265 with five home runs and a team high 97 RBI, while Bid McPhee hit .268 with a team highs in home runs with eight, stolen bases with 40, and runs with 139.
[src:1975-world-series/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Fred Lewis had a team high .318 batting average.
[src:1975-world-series/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, Mullane was the ace of the staff, as he had a 33–27 record with a 3.70 ERA in 56 starts, as he struck out 250 batters in 529.2 innings pitched.
[src:1975-world-series/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings were coming off a second-place finish in the 1885 season, which was their highest placing since winning the 1882 American Association pennant.
[src:1975-world-series/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati was relatively quiet during the off-season; however, Tony Mullane, who had been suspended for the 1885 season for defying his contract, returned and made his Cincinnati debut in 1886.
[src:1975-world-series/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings started the season off slowly, winning only four of their first twelve games to sit in seventh place.
[src:1975-world-series/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati would continue to play mediocre baseball, and would be in eighth place with a 24–35 record, 12.5 games out of first place.
[src:1975-world-series/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings then went on a seven-game winning streak to climb into sixth place to bring their record to 31–35, however, they remained 12.5 games out of first.
[src:1975-world-series/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team eventually broke over the .500 level, reaching a season best three games over .500 with a 50–47 record.
[src:1975-world-series/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] However, Cincinnati faded down the stretch, and finished with a losing record for the first time in team history, as they were 65–73, which was good for fifth place 27.5 games behind the St.
[src:1975-world-series/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1887 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1975-world-series/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team finished in second place in the American Association with a record of 81–45, 14 games behind the St.
[src:1975-world-series/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Following a horrible 1886 season, in which the Red Stockings finished under .500 for the first time in team history, the team hired Gus Schmelz to become the new manager.
[src:1975-world-series/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Louis Maroons of the National League in 1886 to a 43–79 record.
[src:1975-world-series/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] He also managed the Columbus Buckeyes of the American Association in 1883, leading them to a 69–39 record and a second-place finish.
[src:1975-world-series/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati signed George Tebeau to his first professional contract, and acquired Hugh Nicol from the St.
[src:1975-world-series/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Louis Browns in a trade with sent Jack Boyle and $350 to the Browns.
[src:1975-world-series/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Nicol hit .206 with 19 RBI and 38 stolen bases, as well as scoring 44 runs in 67 games in 1886.
[src:1975-world-series/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] John Reilly had a great season, as he hit .306 with a team high ten home runs and had 96 RBI, as well as 50 stolen bases.
[src:1975-world-series/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Pop Corkhill led the club with a .311 batting average, and his 97 RBI tied him with Frank Fennelly for the team high.
[src:1975-world-series/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Nicol led the American Association with 138 stolen bases.
[src:1975-world-series/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, nineteen-year-old Mike Smith emerged as the ace of the staff, as he had a 34–17 record and a league best 2.94 ERA in 52 starts.
[src:1975-world-series/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Tony Mullane also had a solid season, as he had a 31–17 record with a 3.24 ERA in 48 starts.
[src:1975-world-series/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings got off to a fast start, winning their first five games, however, Cincinnati lost six of their next seven games to fall to 6–6.
[src:1975-world-series/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team hovered around the .500 level, as they had a 21–22 record after 43 games, before winning nine of ten to rise up to third place with a 30–23 record.
[src:1975-world-series/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] After going 3–6 in their next nine games, Cincinnati had a season-high ten-game winning streak.
[src:1975-world-series/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] However, they remained in third place, 8.5 games behind the St.
[src:1975-world-series/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings continued to play good baseball for the remainder of the season, as they finished the year in second place with a record of 81–54, fourteen games behind the first-place Browns.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] The **1975 World Series** was the championship series of Major League Baseball's (MLB) 1975 season.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] The 72nd edition of the World Series, it was a best-of-seven playoff played between the American League (AL) champion Boston Red Sox and the National League (NL) champion Cincinnati Reds.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] The Reds won the series, four games to three.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] In 2003, ESPN ranked it the second-greatest World Series ever played, trailing only the 1991 series, while in 2020, Sam Miller of ESPN named it the best World Series ever.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] The Reds, at the height of their Big Red Machine dynasty, recorded a franchise-high 108 victories in 1975 and won the NL West division by 20 games over the Los Angeles Dodgers, then defeated the Pittsburgh Pirates, three games to none, in the NL Championship Series.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] The Red Sox won the AL East division by 4+1⁄2 games over the Baltimore Orioles, then defeated the three-time defending World Series champion Oakland Athletics, three games to none, in the AL Championship Series.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] The sixth game of the World Series was a 12-inning classic at Boston's Fenway Park, which culminated with a walk-off home run by Carlton Fisk to extend the series to seven games.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] The Reds rallied from a 3–0 deficit to win the seventh and deciding game of the series on a ninth-inning single by Joe Morgan.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] It was Cincinnati's third World Series appearance in six years, losing in 1970 to Baltimore and in 1972 to Oakland.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] It was the first of back-to-back championships for the Reds.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] For the Red Sox, the 1975 World Series was their first World Series appearance since losing to St.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] It would be 11 more years until Boston returned to the World Series in 1986, in which they suffered another seven-game loss to the New York Mets.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] This was the fourth time in five years that a seven-game World Series winner (following Pittsburgh in 1971, and Oakland in 1972 and 1973) was outscored.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Reds third baseman Pete Rose was named World Series MVP.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Rose batted .370 with 10 hits and two RBIs and scored 3 runs.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] None of the six umpires in this World Series worked a previous Fall Classic, and two, Art Frantz and George Maloney, would not umpire in another.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Ace pitchers Luis Tiant and Don Gullett were locked in a scoreless duel until the seventh inning.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Tiant led off with a single and later scored Boston's first run on a single by Carl Yastrzemski.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Then the floodgates opened: Reds reliever Clay Carroll walked Carlton Fisk to force in a run, Rico Petrocelli slapped a two-run single, Rick Burleson had an RBI single, and Cecil Cooper ended the scoring with a sacrifice fly.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Tiant finished with a five-hitter against a team that had scored an MLB-high 840 runs during the regular season.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Game 2 proved to be a very pivotal game as the Reds were on the brink of being down two games before rallying for victory in the ninth inning.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Red Sox starter Bill Lee held the Reds to four hits and a run through eight innings.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Johnny Bench led off the ninth with a double to right field.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Lee was then replaced by right-handed closer Dick Drago.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Bench moved to third on a groundout by Tony Pérez.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] After George Foster popped out for the second out, Dave Concepción hit a clutch single up the middle that Boston second baseman Denny Doyle fielded behind second base, but had no play at first as Bench scored to tie the game.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] After Concepcion stole second base, Ken Griffey hit a double into left-center field scoring Concepcion with the game-winner.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Rawly Eastwick retired the Sox in the ninth to get the win and even the series.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] The Reds' only other run scored in the fourth when Joe Morgan walked, went to third on a Bench single, and scored on a Pérez force out.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] The Red Sox sandwiched the Reds' run with single tallies of their own in the first inning on an RBI single by Carlton Fisk, and in the sixth on an RBI single by Rico Petrocelli.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] At home, the Reds prevailed in another squeaker in a game that featured the first major controversy of the series that involved the umpires.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] For nine innings, the game was a homer-fest as each team put three over the wall.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Fisk put the Sox on the board in the second with a homer off Reds starter Gary Nolan.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] The Reds countered by taking a 2–1 lead in the fourth when Tony Pérez walked and Johnny Bench hit a two-run shot off Sox starter Rick Wise.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] The Reds then chased Wise in the fifth when Dave Concepción and César Gerónimo hit back-to-back home runs.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Pete Rose followed with a one-out triple and scored on Joe Morgan's sacrifice fly to give the Reds a 5–1 lead.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] The Sox scratched back in the sixth when Reds reliever Pat Darcy issued consecutive walks to Carl Yastrzemski and Fisk, wild-pitched Yastrzemski to third, and then gave up a sacrifice fly to Fred Lynn.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] In the seventh, former Cincinnati Red Bernie Carbo closed the gap to 5–3 with a pinch-hit homer off Clay Carroll.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] In the top of the ninth, with Reds closer Eastwick on the mound, Rico Petrocelli singled and Evans hit the game-tying home run, sending the game into extra innings.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] After the Red Sox failed to score in the tenth, the Reds sent the bottom of the order to lead off the bottom of the tenth.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Cesar Geronimo led off with a single off Jim Willoughby.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Reds manager Sparky Anderson then sent pinch-hitter Ed Armbrister up to sacrifice in place of reliever Rawly Eastwick.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Armbrister's bunt bounced high near the plate toward the first-base line.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Boston catcher Carlton Fisk was quick to pounce on the ball in front of the plate as Armbrister was slow to get out of the box.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] He hesitated before running and appeared to collide with (or at least impede) Fisk as he was retrieving the ball.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Fisk's hurried throw to second base to force out Geronimo sailed over shortstop Rick Burleson into center field as Geronimo went to third base and Armbrister to second.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Fisk and Boston manager Darrell Johnson argued that Armbrister should have been ruled out for interference, but home plate umpire Larry Barnett ruled otherwise.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] The play stood and the Reds had the potential winning run on third with no outs.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Willoughby then intentionally walked Pete Rose to load the bases and set up a force play at any base.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Johnson then brought in left-hander Roger Moret, to face Ken Griffey, but Anderson countered with right-handed hitting Merv Rettenmund.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] 1, but Joe Morgan knocked in Geronimo with the game-winner by hitting a deep fly to center over a drawn in outfield.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] With the Reds leading the series 2–1, Luis Tiant pitched his second complete game win of the Series.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] More importantly, this win forced the Reds to win at least one of two games at Fenway Park to win the Series.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] The Reds struck first off Tiant in the first on RBI doubles by Ken Griffey and Johnny Bench.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] The Sox, however, would get all the runs they needed in the fourth.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Dwight Evans tied the game with a two-run triple, then Rick Burleson put the Sox ahead by doubling in Evans off Reds starter Fred Norman.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Tiant, continuing his surprising hitting, singled Burleson to third.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Burleson then scored on a Tony Pérez error on a ball hit by Juan Beníquez, while Tiant went to second.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Carl Yastrzemski drove in Tiant with a single for what would turn out to be the winning run.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] The Reds were able to counter with two runs in their half of the fourth on an RBI double by Dave Concepción and an RBI triple by César Gerónimo.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] The Reds had a shot at winning the game in the bottom of the ninth when, with two on and one out, Ken Griffey sent a deep drive into left-center that Fred Lynn made an over the shoulder catch.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Joe Morgan then popped out to first on Tiant's 163rd pitch of the game.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Boston's win tied the series at two games apiece and guaranteed a return to Fenway.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Reds' lefty Don Gullett pitched like an ace as the Reds won their final home game in Game 5 to put Cincinnati on the brink of their first World Series championship in 35 years.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Cincinnati first baseman and cleanup hitter Tony Pérez broke out of an 0–for–15 World Series slump with a pair of home runs while driving in four runs off Boston starter Reggie Cleveland.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Pete Rose contributed an RBI double and Dave Concepción hit a sacrifice fly for the other Reds runs, while Gullett pitched 8+2⁄3 innings, limiting the powerful Boston lineup to five hits.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Reds closer Rawly Eastwick came on to strike out Boston third baseman Rico Petrocelli for the game's final out.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] With a travel day followed by three days of heavy rain in Boston, both pitching staffs got four days of rest.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Red Sox manager Darrell Johnson was afforded the luxury of having his top two starting pitchers, Luis Tiant and Bill Lee, available for Games 6 and 7, respectively, while the Reds were able to have their ace, Don Gullett, available for a potential Game 7 after pitching a gem in Game 5.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] With the Red Sox in a must win situation, Boston's Fred Lynn opened the scoring in the first with a two-out, three-run homer off Reds starter Gary Nolan.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Meanwhile, Tiant breezed through the first four innings, holding the Reds scoreless.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] The Reds finally broke through in the fifth.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] With Ed Armbrister on third and Pete Rose on first, Ken Griffey tripled to deep center field on a ball that Lynn just missed making a leaping catch against the wall.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] He suffered a rib injury, but remained in the game; Lynn told moderator Bob Costas during MLB Network's "Top 20 games in the last 50 years" that, for a short time, he was barely conscious and couldn't feel his legs.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Johnny Bench singled Griffey home to tie the game at 3–3.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] With two outs in the seventh, George Foster put the Reds ahead with a two-run double high off the center field wall.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] In the top of the eighth, César Gerónimo led off and hit the first pitch down the right-field line for a home run to chase Tiant and give the Reds a 6–3 lead.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] In the bottom of the eighth, Reds reliever Pedro Borbón gave up an infield single off his leg to Lynn, and then walked Rico Petrocelli to bring the tying run to the plate.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Rawly Eastwick replaced Borbón, struck out Dwight Evans, and retired Rick Burleson on a line-out to left.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Bernie Carbo was called on to bat for reliever Roger Moret.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Sparky Anderson was on the top step of the dugout, ready to call in left-hander Will McEnaney to pitch to the left-hand hitting Carbo.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Anderson said later that he was concerned that the Sox would call on right-handed Juan Beníquez to pinch hit for Carbo if he made the move.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Carbo looked overmatched by Eastwick, missing on a swing for a 2–2 count; he fouled off two more pitches late, the latter just barely fought off to avoid a strikeout.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] On the next pitch, Carbo tied the game with a three-run home run to center field.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] It was his second pinch-hit homer in the series, tying the record set by Chuck Essegian in 1959.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] In the bottom of the ninth, the Red Sox appeared poised to win.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Denny Doyle walked on four pitches and went to third on a Carl Yastrzemski single; McEnaney, the Reds' seventh pitcher, replaced Eastwick and intentionally walked Carlton Fisk, loading the bases with no outs to face the left-handed hitting Lynn.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] He flied out to Foster in foul territory in left; Doyle tagged up and attempted to score but was thrown out as Bench caught the ball on a bounce and made a sweeping tag from fair territory to nip him just before his hand touched the plate.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] With runners at first and third, McEnaney retired Petrocelli with a ground ball to end the jam.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Rose led off the top of the 11th and was awarded first base after a pitch lightly grazed him.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Griffey bunted, but Fisk's throw forced out Rose at second base.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Joe Morgan hit a deep drive to right off Dick Drago that looked to be for extra bases.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Evans made a leaping catch near the visitors bullpen in deep right to rob Morgan and doubled-up Griffey at first.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] In the top of the 12th, Boston's Rick Wise caught Gerónimo looking with two men on to end the threat.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] In the bottom of the inning, Pat Darcy, the Reds' eighth pitcher, remained in the game after retiring the previous six batters in order.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] As the game passed four hours, Fisk led off; with a 1–0 count, he lifted a sinker down the left-field line and the ball struck the foul pole well above the Green Monster.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] (The cameraman in the scoreboard was supposed to follow the flight of the ball but was distracted by a nearby rat and ended up capturing Fisk instead.) This would be the last time in World Series play that a catcher hit a home run in extra innings until J.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Realmuto did so in the 2022 World Series, 47 years later.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] To date, this is the last World Series game the Reds have lost.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] 7 in ESPN *SportsCentury* Greatest Games of the 20th Century in 1999.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] The game was scoreless until the third inning when Reds starter Don Gullett experienced control problems.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] After giving up an RBI single to Carl Yastrzemski, Gullett walked Carlton Fisk to load the bases.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] He then walked Rico Petrocelli and Dwight Evans to force in two more runs before striking out Rick Burleson for the final out.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Gullett pitched a scoreless fourth before being relieved by Jack Billingham.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] The Reds bullpen pitched five scoreless innings to give the offense a chance to rally.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Boston starter Bill Lee was again sharp, as he shut out the Reds through five innings.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] In the sixth, with Pete Rose on first base and one out, Johnny Bench hit a routine grounder that appeared would be an inning-ending double play.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Shortstop Burleson fielded the grounder and under-handed the ball to Denny Doyle covering second base to force Rose out at second.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] But as Doyle pivoted to make a throw to first base, Rose slid high and hard into Doyle to force an errant throw that sailed into the Boston dugout preventing the double play as Bench moved onto second base.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] On a 1–0 count, Lee threw a blooper pitch to Tony Pérez who slammed the ball over the Green Monster and onto Lansdowne Street for a two-run home run, his third home run in the final three Series games, to draw the Reds to within 3–2.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] The Reds tied it in the seventh when Lee walked Ken Griffey, who stole second and scored on a two-out single to centerfield by Rose off of reliever Roger Moret.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] In the ninth, Boston left-handed rookie reliever Jim Burton entered the game and began by walking the leadoff man Griffey, who was sacrificed to second by César Gerónimo, and went to third on a groundout by Dan Driessen.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Burton then walked Rose to set up a forceout, but Joe Morgan reached down and blooped a low breaking ball into center field to score Griffey with the go-ahead run.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] It was the second time in the series Rose was intentionally walked prior to Morgan driving in the game-winning run.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Morgan, the 1975 National League MVP, also knocked in the game-winner in Game 3.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Will McEnaney retired the Sox in order, with Yastrzemski flying out to center fielder Geronimo to end the game, clinching a World Series championship that had eluded the Reds for 35 years, and extending the Curse of the Bambino to 57 years.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] It would not be broken until 2004, after the Red Sox went 86 years without a championship.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] For the fourth time in five years, the Series went a full seven games and the champions were outscored.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] NBC aired the series on television and radio.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Curt Gowdy and Joe Garagiola alternated the play-by-play between the two mediums along with local team announcers Dick Stockton and Ned Martin (Red Sox) and Marty Brennaman (Reds), while Tony Kubek provided color commentary on the telecasts.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] This was the final World Series play-by-play assignment for Gowdy, who had been NBC's lead baseball announcer since 1966.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] Garagiola took over full-time as NBC's primary play-by-play voice for baseball the following season.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] It was the only World Series broadcast for Stockton (who later became a prominent national sportscaster for CBS, Fox, and TNT) and for Martin.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] This was also the last World Series broadcast for NBC Radio, which had retained exclusive rights to the event since 1957.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] CBS Radio became the exclusive national radio network for MLB beginning the following season.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] This is the earliest World Series for which telecasts of all games survive today in their entirety.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] While portions of many previous Series telecasts also survive, the general practice of the networks in earlier years was to reuse old tapes to save money and space.
[src:1975-world-series/1975-world-series] All subsequent World Series telecasts since this one also have had all their games preserved.
